{
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Overview",
      "content": "Breast cancer is a molecularly heterogeneous disease driven by diverse genomic alterations."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Targetable Genomic Alterations",
      "content": "Germline BRCA1/2 pathogenic variants (PVs) are found in approximately 5% of all breast cancer patients, with higher rates among those with HER2-negative disease [BINV-Q 2, 7]. These mutations impair homologous recombination DNA repair, creating sensitivity to PARP inhibitors such as olaparib (median PFS 7.0 vs 4.2 months; HR 0.58; P < .001) and talazoparib (median PFS 8.6 vs 5.6 months; HR 0.54; P < .001) in the metastatic setting [MS-83]. PIK3CA activating mutations occur in approximately 40% of hormone receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancers and are targetable with PI3K pathway inhibitors; the INAVO120 trial demonstrated improved PFS with fulvestrant/inavolisib/palbociclib versus fulvestrant/placebo/palbociclib (15.0 vs 7.3 months; HR 0.43; 95% CI 0.32–0.59) [BINV-Q 6, MS-63]. ESR1 mutations are frequently detected after exposure to aromatase inhibitors and are targetable with elacestrant, imlunestrant, or vepdegestrant [BINV-Q 6]. AKT1 activating mutations and PTEN inactivating mutations/genomic changes are targetable with capivasertib/fulvestrant (PFS 7.2 vs 3.6 months overall in CAPItello-291) [BINV-Q 6, MS-65]. Germline PALB2 PVs confer sensitivity to olaparib (ORR 75% in a phase II study) [MS-83]. NTRK1/2/3 gene fusions, though rare, are targetable with larotrectinib, entrectinib, or repotrectinib [BINV-Q 7]. Microsatellite instability-high (MSI-H) or mismatch repair deficient (dMMR) tumors respond to pembrolizumab or dostarlimab-gxly [BINV-Q 7]. RET gene fusions are targetable with selpercatinib [BINV-Q 7]. High tumor mutational burden (≥10 mut/Mb) predicts response to pembrolizumab [BINV-Q 7]. HER2 (ERBB2) activating mutations, distinct from HER2 amplification, are targetable with neratinib/trastuzumab/fulvestrant (ORR 39% in the SUMMIT trial) or tucatinib/trastuzumab [BINV-Q 8]. Somatic BRCA1/2 mutations may also predict olaparib benefit (ORR 33% in germline non-BRCA1/2 HR-related gene carriers) [BINV-Q 8]. FGFR1-3 gene fusions/mutations are emerging targets for erdafitinib [BINV-Q 8]."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Gene Expression Profiling",
      "content": "Gene expression profiling reveals distinct molecular subtypes: the 21-gene recurrence score (Oncotype DX) stratifies risk and predicts chemotherapy benefit in HR-positive/HER2-negative disease, with TAILORx demonstrating no chemotherapy benefit for recurrence scores 0–10 and RxPONDER showing chemotherapy benefit for premenopausal patients with scores up to 25 [BINV-N]. The 70-gene (MammaPrint), 50-gene (Prosigna/PAM50), and 12-gene (EndoPredict) assays provide prognostic information [BINV-N]. The Breast Cancer Index predicts benefit from extended endocrine therapy [BINV-N]."
    }
  ],
